</p>
<h2>
    <strong>What Makes Coho (Silver) Salmon Special?</strong>
</h2>
<p>
    Coho salmon are celebrated not just for their fight but for their taste. Their firm, reddish-orange flesh is flavorful and highly sought after. Unlike their Chinook cousins, Coho are smaller—typically ranging between 6 to 12 pounds—but they are aggressive strikers, making them thrilling on light tackle.
</p>
<p>
    Some traits that make Coho unique:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Their acrobatic behavior when hooked.
    </li>
    <li>
        Seasonal returns in large numbers.
    </li>
    <li>
        Excellent table fare with a mild, rich flavor.
    </li>
    <li>
        Compatibility with various fishing styles (spinning, fly, trolling).
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    <strong>When Is the Best Time to Fish for Coho Salmon Near Salem?</strong>
</h2>
<h3>
    <strong>Prime Months for Coho Runs</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    The peak Coho season around Salem generally falls between <strong>mid-September and late October</strong>, though early runs may start in August depending on the river. Hatchery releases are also timed to maximize fish availability during these months.
</p>
<h3>
    <strong>Seasonal Conditions and Water Levels</strong>
</h3>
<p>
    Fall rains are crucial—they raise water levels and trigger upstream movement. Keeping an eye on the weather and river flow gauges can give you a leg up. Low water conditions may delay runs or keep Coho in deeper pools.
</p>
